Project Euler Problem 641 - A long row of dice

Consider a row of n dice all showing 1.

First turn every second die,(2,4,6,)(2,4,6,)(2,4,6,), so that the number showing is increased by 1. Then turn every third die.
The sixth die will now show a 3. Then turn every fourth die and so on until every nth die (only the last die) is turned.
If the die to be turned is showing a 6 then it is changed to show a 1.

Let f(n)f(n)f(n) be the number of dice that are showing a 1 when the process finishes. You are given f(100)=2f{\left( 100 \right )} = 2f(100)=2 and f(108)=69f{\left( 108 \right )} = 69f(108)=69.

Find f(1036)f(1036)f(1036).

Beginning

In order to calculate the amount of dice showing a 1 at the final stage, we need to count the number of numbers whose value have been increased by a multiple of 6. That means the number has 6n6n6n divisors (excluding 1), and therefore 6n+16n+16n+1 divisors where n0n\ge0n0

By the Fundamental theorem of arithmetic every number has a unique prime factorisation. And with a bit of logic, one can determine that a number can only be divided by prime factors and any product of them.
If an integer NNN can be expressed as
N=pipiai=p1a0...pkak,k>0\displaystyle{N = \prod_{p_i}} p_i^{a_i} = p_1^{a_0}*...*p_k^{a_k}, k>0N=pipiai=p1a0...pkak,k>0 where p is a distinct prime

Then the number of divisors of N is given by:

div(N)=pi(ai+1)div(N) = \displaystyle{\prod_{p_i}}(a_i+1)div(N)=pi(ai+1)

We can now relate a numbers prime factorisation to its total number of divisors, to find numbers with 6n+16n+16n+1 divisors.

Applying

Beginning with an integer N with 6n+16n+16n+1 divisors we can get
div(N)=6n+1div(N) = 6n+1div(N)=6n+1
pi(ai+1)=6n+1\displaystyle{\prod_{p_i}}(a_i+1) = 6n+1pi(ai+1)=6n+1

We can simply by using modular arithmetic to arrive at
pi(ai+1)1mod6\displaystyle{\prod_{p_i}}(a_i+1) \equiv 1\mod 6pi(ai+1)1mod6
